{"id":"1601.04699","submitter":"Siddharth Maddali","authors":"Siddharth Maddali, Shlomo Ta'asan, Robert M. Suter","title":"Topology-faithful nonparametric estimation and tracking of bulk\n  interface networks","comments":"Accepted for publication in Computational Materials Science (33\n  pages, 13 figures)","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.commatsci.2016.08.021","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci physics.data-an","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The main focus of this paper is a nonparametric filtering technique for the\nestimation of interface geometry in bulk materials obtainable from modern\nimaging measurements. The filtering methodology relies on an assumed hierarchy\nof topological features present in a typical interface network, such as foam\ninterfaces and grain boundary networks in polycrystalline materials. Each type\nof topological feature is treated in order of rank in the hierarchy, with the\nlower-level feature being filtered subject to the positional constraints\nimposed by the higher-level features. Such a scheme is an alternative to\nexisting surface smoothing/estimation techniques in microstructural materials\nscience, in which the explicit treatment of different elements of the network\ntopology is absent, or at best arbitrarily parameterized. We describe the\nramifications of this technique in the usual microstructural applications in\nwhich the computation of important physical quantities is predicated on the\nprecise estimation of the interface features. As an additional application, we\ndescribe a novel front-tracking algorithm for quantifying the transport of such\ninterfaces.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 17 Jan 2016 23:17:50 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 20 Jan 2016 05:42:22 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 25 Apr 2016 07:02:58 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 17 Aug 2016 04:24:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-12-01"}
